x4freetext: PROGRESS REPORT.
-DIFFERENTIAL NEUTRON ELASTIC SCATTERING CROSS SECTIONS
FOR CR, FE AND NI IN THE ENERGY RANGE 500 TO
STUDSVIK 6 MV VAN DE GRAAFF ACCELERATOR WITH
KLYSTRON BUNCHING SYSTEM.
PROTON-BERYLLIUM, AIR-COOLED BE TARGET(1 MM)
WITH 3.3 MEV PROTONS AND AT A MEAN CURRENT OF 7 MICR-A
.PRIMARY NEUTRON ENERGY DISTRIBUTION HAS A SHARP ENERGY
SIDE DETERMINED BY PRIMARY PROTON ENERGY.  IT WAS
CHOSEN IN SUCH A WAY THAT MAIN PART OF INELASTICALLY
SCATTERED NEUTRONS WOULD HAVE AN ENERGY LESS THAN
500 KEV.
.TOTAL TIME RESOLUTION(FWHM) VARIES FROM 7NS(30 KEV) AT
500 KEV TO 3.5NS(35 KEV) AT 1400 KEV.
.GEOMETRY, 30 MM LONG HOLLOW CYLINDRICAL SAMPLES WITH
OUTER DIAMETER OF 19 MM AND HOLE DIAMETER OF 10 MM.
.NATURAL SAMPLE.
TIME OF FLIGHT.
NE 104 PLASTIC SCINTILLATION DETECTOR, 20 MM
THICK AND 100 MM DIAMETER.
.N-FLUX WAS MONITORED WITH DIRECTION SENSITIVE FAST
NEUTRON DETECTOR (SEE AE-144,1964).
LANE ET AL, ANL-6172(1962).
NEUTRONS.
.TAKEN FROM INTERNAL REPORT BY AUTHOR AS PRIV.COMM.
N.CH
.UNCERTAINTIES IN SCATTERING CROSS-SECTION VALUES ARE
ESTIMATED TO BE ABOUT 7 PERCENT INCUDING ERROR IN
CARBON STANDARD CROSS SECTION.
.TAKING INTO ACCOUNT MULTIPLE SCATTERING, BUT NOT FOR
INTERFERENCE FROM INELASTIC SCATTERING PROCESS.
.INELASTIC CONTRIBUTION BELOW 900 KEV IS LESS THAN
5 MB/SR AND WITHIN STATISTICAL ERROR OF MEASUREMENT.
